by Noel McCann from Dream Team (Team 2)





Based on the StartUp Investments (Crunchbase) dataset - Information about startup companies and investment via Crunchbase https://www.kaggle.com/arindam235/startup-investments-crunchbase


Introduction to the dataset¶

StartUp Investments (Crunchbase): https://www.kaggle.com/arindam235/startup-investments-crunchbase

  • The dataset used for this analysis was downloaded from Kaggle but the source of the data is from Crunchbase. The site contains financial information and funding rounds for private and public companies involved in services such as payments and BNPL.


The dataset consists financial data relating to investments in startups. This data includes:

  • startup name
  • url
  • market category
  • status (operating, acquired, closed)
  • location: country, city, region
  • funding: total funding in usd, type of funding (including, but not limited to, seed, angel, debt taken, venture capital, & funding rounds)


The goal of this workbook is to provide a financial analysis on companies in the fintech space. We specifically concentrated on companies that specialize in finance, payments, and BNPL to see where companies such as Afterpay and Klarna have performed in the space, and how Square stands to benefit from entering this market.

Focusing our study: Filtering and Identifying¶

Given Crunchbase's large amount of data, it would be overwhelming to go through the entire dataset. Given our goal to financially analyze the performance of private and public fintech companies, filtering needs to be done to clean up the dataset. First, we took a look at the structure and brief contents of the data, such as the columns. Afterwards, we selected a subset of columns relevant to our focus on Fintech.

Data clean up stage¶

  • At this stage, we wanted to make sure some of the spaces, commas, dtypes, date types and decimal places were correct and usable for our purposes. We also dropped columns with zero values and grouped countries by market category.
In [27]:
#cleaning column names and reformatting the data
#Column names had some empty spaces
investments.columns = investments.columns.str.replace(' ','')
In [28]:
# Removed the commas from the total funding to prevent later calculations from breaking.
investments.funding_total_usd = investments.funding_total_usd.str.replace(',','')
# Changed the total funding from string to float. USD is a currency, so we need to track via float.
investments.funding_total_usd = pd.to_numeric(investments.funding_total_usd, errors='coerce')
# Changed the data type for column founded_at to datetime type
investments['founded_at'] = pd.to_datetime(investments['founded_at'], errors = 'coerce' )
# Changed the data type for column first_funding_at to datetime type
investments.first_funding_at = pd.to_datetime(investments.first_funding_at, format='%Y/%m/%d', errors='coerce')
# Groupped Data by industry market.
investments.groupby(' market ').mean()
